   MMoouunntt ooppttiioonnss ffoorr iissoo99666600
       ISO 9660 is a standard describing a filesystem structure to be used on CD-ROMs. (This filesystem type is also seen on some DVDs.  See also the _u_d_f filesystem.)

       Normal  _i_s_o_9_6_6_0  filenames  appear in an 8.3 format (i.e., DOS-like restrictions on filename length), and in addition all characters are in upper case.  Also there is no field for
       file ownership, protection, number of links, provision for block/character devices, etc.

       Rock Ridge is an extension to iso9660 that provides all of these UNIX-like features.  Basically there are extensions to each directory record that supply all of the additional in‐
       formation, and when Rock Ridge is in use, the filesystem is indistinguishable from a normal UNIX filesystem (except that it is read-only, of course).

       nnoorroocckk Disable the use of Rock Ridge extensions, even if available.  Cf. mmaapp.

       nnoojjoolliieett
              Disable the use of Microsoft Joliet extensions, even if available.  Cf. mmaapp.

       cchheecckk=={rr[eellaaxxeedd]|ss[ttrriicctt]}
              With  cchheecckk==rreellaaxxeedd,  a filename is first converted to lower case before doing the lookup.  This is probably only meaningful together with nnoorroocckk and mmaapp==nnoorrmmaall.  (Default:
              cchheecckk==ssttrriicctt.)

       uuiidd==_v_a_l_u_e and ggiidd==_v_a_l_u_e
              Give all files in the filesystem the indicated user or group id, possibly overriding the information found in the Rock Ridge extensions.  (Default: uuiidd==00,,ggiidd==00.)

       mmaapp=={nn[oorrmmaall]|oo[ffff]|aa[ccoorrnn]}
              For non-Rock Ridge volumes, normal name translation maps upper to lower case ASCII, drops a trailing `;1', and converts `;' to `.'.  With mmaapp==ooffff  no  name  translation  is
              done.  See nnoorroocckk.  (Default: mmaapp==nnoorrmmaall.)  mmaapp==aaccoorrnn is like mmaapp==nnoorrmmaall but also apply Acorn extensions if present.

       mmooddee==_v_a_l_u_e
              For non-Rock Ridge volumes, give all files the indicated mode.  (Default: read and execute permission for everybody.)  Octal mode values require a leading 0.

       uunnhhiiddee Also show hidden and associated files.  (If the ordinary files and the associated or hidden files have the same filenames, this may make the ordinary files inaccessible.)

       bblloocckk=={551122|11002244|22004488}
              Set the block size to the indicated value.  (Default: bblloocckk==11002244.)

       ccoonnvv==_m_o_d_e
              This option is obsolete and may fail or being ignored.

       ccrruufftt  If  the  high  byte  of  the file length contains other garbage, set this mount option to ignore the high order bits of the file length.  This implies that a file cannot be
              larger than 16 MB.

       sseessssiioonn==_x
              Select number of session on multisession CD.

       ssbbsseeccttoorr==_x_x_x
              Session begins from sector xxx.

       The following options are the same as for vfat and specifying them only makes sense when using discs encoded using Microsoft's Joliet extensions.

       iioocchhaarrsseett==_v_a_l_u_e
              Character set to use for converting 16 bit Unicode characters on CD to 8 bit characters.  The default is iso8859-1.

       uuttff88   Convert 16 bit Unicode characters on CD to UTF-8.

   MMoouunntt ooppttiioonnss ffoorr jjffss
       iioocchhaarrsseett==_n_a_m_e
              Character set to use for converting from Unicode to ASCII.  The default is to do no conversion.  Use iioocchhaarrsseett==uuttff88 for UTF8 translations.  This requires CONFIG_NLS_UTF8 to
              be set in the kernel _._c_o_n_f_i_g file.

       rreessiizzee==_v_a_l_u_e
              Resize  the  volume  to  _v_a_l_u_e  blocks.  JFS only supports growing a volume, not shrinking it.  This option is only valid during a remount, when the volume is mounted read-
              write.  The rreessiizzee keyword with no value will grow the volume to the full size of the partition.

       nnooiinntteeggrriittyy
              Do not write to the journal.  The primary use of this option is to allow for higher performance when restoring a volume from backup media.  The integrity of the  volume  is
              not guaranteed if the system abnormally ends.

       iinntteeggrriittyy
              Default.   Commit metadata changes to the journal.  Use this option to remount a volume where the nnooiinntteeggrriittyy option was previously specified in order to restore normal be‐
              havior.

       eerrrroorrss=={ccoonnttiinnuuee|rreemmoouunntt--rroo|ppaanniicc}
              Define the behavior when an error is encountered.  (Either ignore errors and just mark the filesystem erroneous and continue, or remount the filesystem read-only, or  panic
              and halt the system.)

       nnooqquuoottaa|qquuoottaa|uussrrqquuoottaa|ggrrppqquuoottaa
              These options are accepted but ignored.

   MMoouunntt ooppttiioonnss ffoorr mmssddooss
       See mount options for fat.  If the _m_s_d_o_s filesystem detects an inconsistency, it reports an error and sets the file system read-only.  The filesystem can be made writable again by
       remounting it.

   MMoouunntt ooppttiioonnss ffoorr nnccppffss
       Just like _n_f_s, the _n_c_p_f_s implementation expects a binary argument (a _s_t_r_u_c_t _n_c_p___m_o_u_n_t___d_a_t_a) to the mount system call.  This argument is constructed by nnccppmmoouunntt(8) and the  current
       version of mmoouunntt (2.12) does not know anything about ncpfs.

   MMoouunntt ooppttiioonnss ffoorr nnttffss
       iioocchhaarrsseett==_n_a_m_e
              Character set to use when returning file names.  Unlike VFAT, NTFS suppresses names that contain nonconvertible characters.  Deprecated.

       nnllss==_n_a_m_e
              New name for the option earlier called _i_o_c_h_a_r_s_e_t.

       uuttff88   Use UTF-8 for converting file names.

       uunnii__xxllaattee=={00|11|22}
              For  0  (or  `no' or `false'), do not use escape sequences for unknown Unicode characters.  For 1 (or `yes' or `true') or 2, use vfat-style 4-byte escape sequences starting
              with ":".  Here 2 give a little-endian encoding and 1 a byteswapped bigendian encoding.

       ppoossiixx==[[00||11]]
              If enabled (posix=1), the filesystem distinguishes between upper and lower case.  The 8.3 alias names are presented as hard links instead of being suppressed.  This  option
              is obsolete.

       uuiidd==_v_a_l_u_e, ggiidd==_v_a_l_u_e and uummaasskk==_v_a_l_u_e
              Set the file permission on the filesystem.  The umask value is given in octal.  By default, the files are owned by root and not readable by somebody else.

   MMoouunntt ooppttiioonnss ffoorr oovveerrllaayy
       Since Linux 3.18 the overlay pseudo filesystem implements a union mount for other filesystems.

       An overlay filesystem combines two filesystems - an uuppppeerr filesystem and a lloowweerr filesystem.  When a name exists in both filesystems, the object in the upper filesystem is visible
       while the object in the lower filesystem is either hidden or, in the case of directories, merged with the upper object.

       The lower filesystem can be any filesystem supported by Linux and does not need to be writable.  The lower filesystem can even be another overlayfs.   The  upper  filesystem  will
       normally be writable and if it is it must support the creation of trusted.* extended attributes, and must provide a valid d_type in readdir responses, so NFS is not suitable.

       A read-only overlay of two read-only filesystems may use any filesystem type.  The options lloowweerrddiirr and uuppppeerrddiirr are combined into a merged directory by using:

              mmoouunntt --tt oovveerrllaayy  oovveerrllaayy  \\
                --oolloowweerrddiirr==//lloowweerr,,uuppppeerrddiirr==//uuppppeerr,,wwoorrkkddiirr==//wwoorrkk  //mmeerrggeedd

       lloowweerrddiirr==_d_i_r_e_c_t_o_r_y
              Any filesystem, does not need to be on a writable filesystem.

       uuppppeerrddiirr==_d_i_r_e_c_t_o_r_y
              The upperdir is normally on a writable filesystem.

       wwoorrkkddiirr==_d_i_r_e_c_t_o_r_y
              The workdir needs to be an empty directory on the same filesystem as upperdir.

   MMoouunntt ooppttiioonnss ffoorr rreeiisseerrffss
       Reiserfs is a journaling filesystem.

       ccoonnvv   Instructs  version  3.6  reiserfs  software to mount a version 3.5 filesystem, using the 3.6 format for newly created objects.  This filesystem will no longer be compatible
              with reiserfs 3.5 tools.

       hhaasshh=={rruuppaassoovv|tteeaa|rr55|ddeetteecctt}
              Choose which hash function reiserfs will use to find files within directories.

              rruuppaassoovv
                     A hash invented by Yury Yu. Rupasov.  It is fast and preserves locality, mapping lexicographically close file names to close hash values.  This option should not  be
                     used, as it causes a high probability of hash collisions.

              tteeaa    A Davis-Meyer function implemented by Jeremy Fitzhardinge.  It uses hash permuting bits in the name.  It gets high randomness and, therefore, low probability of hash
                     collisions at some CPU cost.  This may be used if EHASHCOLLISION errors are experienced with the r5 hash.

              rr55     A modified version of the rupasov hash.  It is used by default and is the best choice unless the filesystem has huge directories and unusual file-name patterns.

              ddeetteecctt Instructs _m_o_u_n_t to detect which hash function is in use by examining the filesystem being mounted, and to write this information into the reiserfs superblock.   This
                     is only useful on the first mount of an old format filesystem.

       hhaasshheedd__rreellooccaattiioonn
              Tunes the block allocator.  This may provide performance improvements in some situations.

       nnoo__uunnhhaasshheedd__rreellooccaattiioonn
              Tunes the block allocator.  This may provide performance improvements in some situations.

       nnoobboorrddeerr
              Disable the border allocator algorithm invented by Yury Yu. Rupasov.  This may provide performance improvements in some situations.

       nnoolloogg  Disable  journaling.   This will provide slight performance improvements in some situations at the cost of losing reiserfs's fast recovery from crashes.  Even with this op‐
              tion turned on, reiserfs still performs all journaling operations, save for actual writes into its journaling area.  Implementation of _n_o_l_o_g is a work in progress.

       nnoottaaiill By default, reiserfs stores small files and `file tails' directly into its tree.  This confuses some utilities such as LLIILLOO(8).  This option is used to disable  packing  of
              files into the tree.

       rreeppllaayyoonnllyy
              Replay the transactions which are in the journal, but do not actually mount the filesystem.  Mainly used by _r_e_i_s_e_r_f_s_c_k.

       rreessiizzee==_n_u_m_b_e_r
              A  remount  option  which permits online expansion of reiserfs partitions.  Instructs reiserfs to assume that the device has _n_u_m_b_e_r blocks.  This option is designed for use
              with devices which are under logical volume management (LVM).  There is a special _r_e_s_i_z_e_r utility which can be obtained from _f_t_p_:_/_/_f_t_p_._n_a_m_e_s_y_s_._c_o_m_/_p_u_b_/_r_e_i_s_e_r_f_s_p_r_o_g_s.

       uusseerr__xxaattttrr
              Enable Extended User Attributes.  See the aattttrr(5) manual page.

       aaccll    Enable POSIX Access Control Lists.  See the aaccll(5) manual page.

       bbaarrrriieerr==nnoonnee / bbaarrrriieerr==fflluusshh
              This disables / enables the use of write barriers in the journaling code.  barrier=none disables, barrier=flush enables (default).  This also requires an IO stack which can
              support  barriers, and if reiserfs gets an error on a barrier write, it will disable barriers again with a warning.  Write barriers enforce proper on-disk ordering of jour‐
              nal commits, making volatile disk write caches safe to use, at some performance penalty.  If your disks are battery-backed in one way or  another,  disabling  barriers  may
              safely improve performance.

   MMoouunntt ooppttiioonnss ffoorr uubbiiffss
       UBIFS is a flash filesystem which works on top of UBI volumes.  Note that aattiimmee is not supported and is always turned off.

       The device name may be specified as
              uubbiiXX__YY UBI device number XX, volume number YY

              uubbiiYY   UBI device number 00, volume number YY

              uubbiiXX::NNAAMMEE
                     UBI device number XX, volume with name NNAAMMEE

              uubbii::NNAAMMEE
                     UBI device number 00, volume with name NNAAMMEE
       Alternative !!  separator may be used instead of ::.

       The following mount options are available:

       bbuullkk__rreeaadd
              Enable  bulk-read.   VFS read-ahead is disabled because it slows down the file system.  Bulk-Read is an internal optimization.  Some flashes may read faster if the data are
              read at one go, rather than at several read requests.  For example, OneNAND can do "read-while-load" if it reads more than one NAND page.

       nnoo__bbuullkk__rreeaadd
              Do not bulk-read.  This is the default.

       cchhkk__ddaattaa__ccrrcc
              Check data CRC-32 checksums.  This is the default.

       nnoo__cchhkk__ddaattaa__ccrrcc.
              Do not check data CRC-32 checksums.  With this option, the filesystem does not check CRC-32 checksum for data, but it does check it for the internal  indexing  information.
              This option only affects reading, not writing.  CRC-32 is always calculated when writing the data.

       ccoommpprr=={nnoonnee|llzzoo|zzlliibb}
              Select the default compressor which is used when new files are written.  It is still possible to read compressed files if mounted with the nnoonnee option.

   MMoouunntt ooppttiioonnss ffoorr uuddff
       UDF  is  the  "Universal  Disk  Format"  filesystem  defined by OSTA, the Optical Storage Technology Association, and is often used for DVD-ROM, frequently in the form of a hybrid
       UDF/ISO-9660 filesystem. It is, however, perfectly usable by itself on disk drives, flash drives and other block devices.  See also _i_s_o_9_6_6_0.

       uuiidd==   Make all files in the filesystem belong to the given user.  uid=forget can be specified independently of (or usually in addition to) uid=<user> and results in UDF not stor‐
              ing  uids  to  the  media. In fact the recorded uid is the 32-bit overflow uid -1 as defined by the UDF standard.  The value is given as either <user> which is a valid user
              name or the corresponding decimal user id, or the special string "forget".

       ggiidd==   Make all files in the filesystem belong to the given group.  gid=forget can be specified independently of (or usually in addition to) gid=<group> and  results  in  UDF  not
              storing  gids  to  the  media. In fact the recorded gid is the 32-bit overflow gid -1 as defined by the UDF standard.  The value is given as either <group> which is a valid
              group name or the corresponding decimal group id, or the special string "forget".

       uummaasskk== Mask out the given permissions from all inodes read from the filesystem.  The value is given in octal.

       mmooddee==  If mode= is set the permissions of all non-directory inodes read from the filesystem will be set to the given mode. The value is given in octal.

       ddmmooddee== If dmode= is set the permissions of all directory inodes read from the filesystem will be set to the given dmode. The value is given in octal.

       bbss==    Set the block size. Default value prior to kernel version 2.6.30 was 2048. Since 2.6.30 and prior to 4.11 it was logical device block size with fallback to 2048. Since 4.11
              it is logical block size with fallback to any valid block size between logical device block size and 4096.

              For other details see the mmkkuuddffffss(8) 2.0+ manpage, sections CCOOMMPPAATTIIBBIILLIITTYY and BBLLOOCCKK SSIIZZEE.

       uunnhhiiddee Show otherwise hidden files.

       uunnddeelleettee
              Show deleted files in lists.

       aaddiinniiccbb
              Embed data in the inode. (default)

       nnooaaddiinniiccbb
              Don't embed data in the inode.

       sshhoorrttaadd
              Use short UDF address descriptors.

       lloonnggaadd Use long UDF address descriptors. (default)

       nnoossttrriicctt
              Unset strict conformance.

       iioocchhaarrsseett==
              Set the NLS character set. This requires kernel compiled with CONFIG_UDF_NLS option.

       uuttff88   Set the UTF-8 character set.

   MMoouunntt ooppttiioonnss ffoorr ddeebbuuggggiinngg aanndd ddiissaasstteerr rreeccoovveerryy
       nnoovvrrss  Ignore the Volume Recognition Sequence and attempt to mount anyway.

       sseessssiioonn==
              Select the session number for multi-session recorded optical media. (default= last session)

       aanncchhoorr==
              Override standard anchor location. (default= 256)

       llaassttbblloocckk==
              Set the last block of the filesystem.

   UUnnuusseedd hhiissttoorriiccaall mmoouunntt ooppttiioonnss tthhaatt mmaayy bbee eennccoouunntteerreedd aanndd sshhoouulldd bbee rreemmoovveedd
       uuiidd==iiggnnoorree
              Ignored, use uid=<user> instead.

       ggiidd==iiggnnoorree
              Ignored, use gid=<group> instead.

       vvoolluummee==
              Unimplemented and ignored.

       ppaarrttiittiioonn==
              Unimplemented and ignored.

       ffiilleesseett==
              Unimplemented and ignored.

       rroooottddiirr==
              Unimplemented and ignored.

   MMoouunntt ooppttiioonnss ffoorr uuffss
       uuffssttyyppee==_v_a_l_u_e
              UFS  is  a filesystem widely used in different operating systems.  The problem are differences among implementations.  Features of some implementations are undocumented, so
              its hard to recognize the type of ufs automatically.  That's why the user must specify the type of ufs by mount option.  Possible values are:

              oolldd    Old format of ufs, this is the default, read only.  (Don't forget to give the -r option.)

              4444bbssdd  For filesystems created by a BSD-like system (NetBSD, FreeBSD, OpenBSD).

              uuffss22   Used in FreeBSD 5.x supported as read-write.

              55xxbbssdd  Synonym for ufs2.

              ssuunn    For filesystems created by SunOS or Solaris on Sparc.

              ssuunnxx8866 For filesystems created by Solaris on x86.

              hhpp     For filesystems created by HP-UX, read-only.

              nneexxttsstteepp
                     For filesystems created by NeXTStep (on NeXT station) (currently read only).

              nneexxttsstteepp--ccdd
                     For NextStep CDROMs (block_size == 2048), read-only.

              ooppeennsstteepp
                     For filesystems created by OpenStep (currently read only).  The same filesystem type is also used by Mac OS X.

       oonneerrrroorr==_v_a_l_u_e
              Set behavior on error:

              ppaanniicc  If an error is encountered, cause a kernel panic.

              [lloocckk|uummoouunntt|rreeppaaiirr]
                     These mount options don't do anything at present; when an error is encountered only a console message is printed.

   MMoouunntt ooppttiioonnss ffoorr uummssddooss
       See mount options for msdos.  The ddoottssOOKK option is explicitly killed by _u_m_s_d_o_s.

   MMoouunntt ooppttiioonnss ffoorr vvffaatt
       First of all, the mount options for _f_a_t are recognized.  The ddoottssOOKK option is explicitly killed by _v_f_a_t.  Furthermore, there are

       uunnii__xxllaattee
              Translate unhandled Unicode characters to special escaped sequences.  This lets you backup and restore filenames that are created with any Unicode characters.  Without this
              option,  a  '?' is used when no translation is possible.  The escape character is ':' because it is otherwise invalid on the vfat filesystem.  The escape sequence that gets
              used, where u is the Unicode character, is: ':', (u & 0x3f), ((u>>6) & 0x3f), (u>>12).

       ppoossiixx  Allow two files with names that only differ in case.  This option is obsolete.

       nnoonnuummttaaiill
              First try to make a short name without sequence number, before trying _n_a_m_e_~_n_u_m_._e_x_t.

       uuttff88   UTF8 is the filesystem safe 8-bit encoding of Unicode that is used by the console.  It can be enabled for the filesystem with this option or disabled with  utf8=0,  utf8=no
              or utf8=false.  If `uni_xlate' gets set, UTF8 gets disabled.

       sshhoorrttnnaammee==_m_o_d_e
              Defines  the  behavior  for creation and display of filenames which fit into 8.3 characters.  If a long name for a file exists, it will always be the preferred one for dis‐
              play.  There are four _m_o_d_es:

              lloowweerr  Force the short name to lower case upon display; store a long name when the short name is not all upper case.

              wwiinn9955  Force the short name to upper case upon display; store a long name when the short name is not all upper case.

              wwiinnnntt  Display the short name as is; store a long name when the short name is not all lower case or all upper case.

              mmiixxeedd  Display the short name as is; store a long name when the short name is not all upper case.  This mode is the default since Linux 2.6.32.

   MMoouunntt ooppttiioonnss ffoorr uussbbffss
       ddeevvuuiidd==_u_i_d and ddeevvggiidd==_g_i_d and ddeevvmmooddee==_m_o_d_e
              Set the owner and group and mode of the device files in the usbfs filesystem (default: uid=gid=0, mode=0644).  The mode is given in octal.

       bbuussuuiidd==_u_i_d and bbuussggiidd==_g_i_d and bbuussmmooddee==_m_o_d_e
              Set the owner and group and mode of the bus directories in the usbfs filesystem (default: uid=gid=0, mode=0555).  The mode is given in octal.

       lliissttuuiidd==_u_i_d and lliissttggiidd==_g_i_d and lliissttmmooddee==_m_o_d_e
              Set the owner and group and mode of the file _d_e_v_i_c_e_s (default: uid=gid=0, mode=0444).  The mode is given in octal.

TTHHEE LLOOOOPP DDEEVVIICCEE
       One further possible type is a mount via the loop device.  For example, the command

              mmoouunntt //ttmmpp//ddiisskk..iimmgg //mmnntt --tt vvffaatt --oo lloooopp==//ddeevv//lloooopp33

       will set up the loop device _/_d_e_v_/_l_o_o_p_3 to correspond to the file _/_t_m_p_/_d_i_s_k_._i_m_g, and then mount this device on _/_m_n_t.

       If no explicit loop device is mentioned (but just an option `--oo lloooopp' is given), then mmoouunntt will try to find some unused loop device and use that, for example

              mmoouunntt //ttmmpp//ddiisskk..iimmgg //mmnntt --oo lloooopp

       The mount command aauuttoommaattiiccaallllyy creates a loop device from a regular file if a filesystem type is not specified or the filesystem is known for libblkid, for example:

              mmoouunntt //ttmmpp//ddiisskk..iimmgg //mmnntt

              mmoouunntt --tt eexxtt44 //ttmmpp//ddiisskk..iimmgg //mmnntt

       This type of mount knows about three options, namely lloooopp, ooffffsseett and ssiizzeelliimmiitt, that are really options to lloosseettuupp(8).  (These options can be used in addition to  those  specific
       to the filesystem type.)

       Since Linux 2.6.25 auto-destruction of loop devices is supported, meaning that any loop device allocated by mmoouunntt will be freed by uummoouunntt independently of _/_e_t_c_/_m_t_a_b.

       You can also free a loop device by hand, using lloosseettuupp --dd or uummoouunntt --dd.

       Since util-linux v2.29 mount command re-uses the loop device rather than initialize a new device if the same backing file is already used for some loop device with the same offset
       and sizelimit. This is necessary to avoid a filesystem corruption.

RREETTUURRNN CCOODDEESS
       mmoouunntt has the following return codes (the bits can be ORed):

       00      success

       11      incorrect invocation or permissions

       22      system error (out of memory, cannot fork, no more loop devices)

       44      internal mmoouunntt bug

       88      user interrupt

       1166     problems writing or locking /etc/mtab

       3322     mount failure

       6644     some mount succeeded

       The command mmoouunntt --aa returns 0 (all succeeded), 32 (all failed), or 64 (some failed, some succeeded).

EEXXTTEERRNNAALL HHEELLPPEERRSS
       The syntax of external mount helpers is:

           //ssbbiinn//mmoouunntt.._s_u_f_f_i_x _s_p_e_c _d_i_r [--ssffnnvv] [--NN _n_a_m_e_s_p_a_c_e] [--oo _o_p_t_i_o_n_s] [--tt _t_y_p_e.._s_u_b_t_y_p_e]

       where the _s_u_f_f_i_x is the filesystem type and the --ssffnnvvooNN options have the same meaning as the normal mount options.  The --tt option is used for  filesystems  with  subtypes  support
       (for example //ssbbiinn//mmoouunntt..ffuussee --tt ffuussee..sssshhffss).

       The  command  mmoouunntt  does not pass the mount options uunnbbiinnddaabbllee, rruunnbbiinnddaabbllee, pprriivvaattee, rrpprriivvaattee, ssllaavvee, rrssllaavvee, sshhaarreedd, rrsshhaarreedd, aauuttoo, nnooaauuttoo, ccoommmmeenntt, xx--**, lloooopp, ooffffsseett and ssiizzee‐‐
       lliimmiitt to the mount.<suffix> helpers.  All other options are used in a comma-separated list as argument to the --oo option.

FFIILLEESS
       See also "TThhee ffiilleess //eettcc//ffssttaabb,, //eettcc//mmttaabb aanndd //pprroocc//mmoouunnttss" section above.

       _/_e_t_c_/_f_s_t_a_b        filesystem table

       _/_r_u_n_/_m_o_u_n_t        libmount private runtime directory

       _/_e_t_c_/_m_t_a_b         table of mounted filesystems or symlink to /proc/mounts

       _/_e_t_c_/_m_t_a_b_~        lock file (unused on systems with mtab symlink)

       _/_e_t_c_/_m_t_a_b_._t_m_p     temporary file (unused on systems with mtab symlink)

       _/_e_t_c_/_f_i_l_e_s_y_s_t_e_m_s  a list of filesystem types to try

EENNVVIIRROONNMMEENNTT
       LIBMOUNT_FSTAB=<path>
              overrides the default location of the fstab file (ignored for suid)

       LIBMOUNT_MTAB=<path>
              overrides the default location of the mtab file (ignored for suid)

       LIBMOUNT_DEBUG=all
              enables libmount debug output

       LIBBLKID_DEBUG=all
              enables libblkid debug output

       LOOPDEV_DEBUG=all
              enables loop device setup debug output

SSEEEE AALLSSOO
       mmoouunntt(2), uummoouunntt(2), uummoouunntt(8), ffssttaabb(5), nnffss(5), xxffss(5), ee22llaabbeell(8), ffiinnddmmnntt(8), lloosseettuupp(8), mmkkee22ffss(8), mmoouunnttdd(8), nnffssdd(8), sswwaappoonn(8), ttuunnee22ffss(8), xxffss__aaddmmiinn(8)

BBUUGGSS
       It is possible for a corrupted filesystem to cause a crash.

       Some Linux filesystems don't support --oo ssyynncc nor --oo ddiirrssyynncc (the ext2, ext3, ext4, fat and vfat filesystems _d_o support synchronous updates (a la BSD) when mounted  with  the  ssyynncc
       option).

       The --oo rreemmoouunntt may not be able to change mount parameters (all _e_x_t_2_f_s-specific parameters, except ssbb, are changeable with a remount, for example, but you can't change ggiidd or uummaasskk
       for the _f_a_t_f_s).

       It is possible that the files _/_e_t_c_/_m_t_a_b and _/_p_r_o_c_/_m_o_u_n_t_s don't match on systems with a regular mtab file.  The first file is based only on the mount command options, but the  con‐
       tent  of  the second file also depends on the kernel and others settings (e.g. on a remote NFS server -- in certain cases the mount command may report unreliable information about
       an NFS mount point and the /proc/mounts file usually contains more reliable information.)  This is another reason to replace the mtab file with a symlink to the _/_p_r_o_c_/_m_o_u_n_t_s file.

       Checking files on NFS filesystems referenced by file descriptors (i.e. the ffccnnttll and iiooccttll families of functions) may lead to inconsistent results due to the lack of a consistency
       check in the kernel even if noac is used.

       The  lloooopp  option with the ooffffsseett or ssiizzeelliimmiitt options used may fail when using older kernels if the mmoouunntt command can't confirm that the size of the block device has been config‐
       ured as requested.  This situation can be worked around by using the lloosseettuupp command manually before calling mmoouunntt with the configured loop device.

HHIISSTTOORRYY
       A mmoouunntt command existed in Version 5 AT&T UNIX.

AAUUTTHHOORRSS
       Karel Zak <kzak@redhat.com>

AAVVAAIILLAABBIILLIITTYY
       The mount command is part of the util-linux package and is available from https://www.kernel.org/pub/linux/utils/util-linux/.

